{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569528"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:28:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:28:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22267"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22267"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.08,0.07,0.18,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15232"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107916"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15232"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22267"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90333"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"2440"},{"type":"tags","id":"2474"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40253"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40254"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44446"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107916"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a three-week history of a painless, slowly enlarging skin lesion on his left calf. He lives in coastal Victoria and enjoys gardening. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 3 cm diameter ulcer with undermined edges on his left calf (image). The surrounding skin is indurated but not tender. There is no lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA wound swab PCR confirms the presence of \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium ulcerans\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rifampicin and clarithromycin","Doxycycline monotherapy","Immediate surgical excision","Flucloxacillin and metronidazole","Topical mupirocin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a confirmed diagnosis of Buruli ulcer (Bairnsdale ulcer) caused by \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium ulcerans\u003C/em\u003E. The most appropriate treatment is \u003Cstrong\u003Erifampicin and clarithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E combination therapy for eight weeks. This antibiotic regimen has been shown to be highly effective, with cure rates exceeding 95% when started early. The combination targets the organism effectively and reduces the risk of resistance development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline monotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for Buruli ulcer. While doxycycline has some activity against mycobacteria, monotherapy is insufficient and combination therapy is the standard of care to ensure adequate treatment and prevent resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate surgical excision\u003C/strong\u003E was historically the primary treatment for Buruli ulcer, but with the advent of effective antibiotic therapy, surgery is now reserved for large lesions (\u0026gt;10 cm), lesions over joints, or those that fail to respond to medical therapy. For this 3 cm lesion, antibiotic therapy should be tried first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlucloxacillin and metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for treating secondary bacterial infections or necrotising soft tissue infections, but they have no activity against \u003Cem\u003EM. ulcerans\u003C/em\u003E. This combination would be ineffective for treating the underlying mycobacterial infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical mupirocin\u003C/strong\u003E is used for superficial bacterial skin infections such as impetigo. It has no activity against mycobacteria and would not penetrate adequately to treat the deep tissue involvement characteristic of Buruli ulcer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to antibiotic therapy, wound care is an important component of management. This includes regular dressing changes, debridement of necrotic tissue if necessary, and monitoring for signs of healing. Most patients can be managed as outpatients with regular follow-up to assess treatment response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Buruli ulcer is treated with combination antibiotic therapy using rifampicin and clarithromycin for eight weeks.","Early antibiotic treatment of Buruli ulcer can prevent the need for surgical intervention.","Wound care and monitoring for treatment response are essential components of Buruli ulcer management."],"references":["Wong CCW, Muhi S, O\u2019Brien DP. An overview of Buruli ulcer in Australia. Aust J Gen Pract 2024;53(9):671\u2013676. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2024/september/an-overview-of-buruli-ulcer-in-australia","Buruli ulcer. In: DermNet NZ [Online]. 2014 Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/buruli-ulcer"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90333"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22267"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20815"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"medi